  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Published in 2017 by Peter Lang Verlag within the established <em>Travail et Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 / Work and Society</em> series, <em>Austerity and the Implementation of the Europe 2020 Strategy in Spain</em> by Javier Ramos and Esther del Campo offers a focused political-science examination of how fiscal austerity shaped Spain's pursuit of EU growth and social targets. The book has accumulated three citations across peer-reviewed and scholarly contexts, places in approximately the 80th percentile of comparable works by citation impact, and remains openly accessible, supporting its continued discoverability.</p>\n\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The book's core contribution lies in tracing the tension between the European Union's ambitious Europe 2020 agenda\u2014oriented toward smart, sustainable, and inclusive growth\u2014and the severe fiscal consolidation measures imposed on Spain during the post-2008 economic crisis. By situating this tension within a rigorous political-science and public-policy framework, Ramos and del Campo provide one of the more granular country-level accounts of how austerity conditionality interacted with, and frequently undermined, the strategy's social and employment goals. The work was edited with contributions from Sergio Gonz\u00e1lez Begega and E. del Pino, signalling engagement from scholars active in Spanish and comparative European welfare-state research.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">Scholarly uptake, while modest in absolute terms, shows a meaningful spread across output types and geographies. Citations have arrived from a book, a book chapter, and a journal article, spanning outlets in Spain, Finland, and Brazil. Notably, the work was drawn upon in a comparative study of education and inequality across Finland, Spain, and Brazil, and in a Spanish legal journal article on social innovation in the EU \u2014 contexts that reflect the book's relevance to debates about equity, human capital, and social governance under austerity. The citing institutions include Universidad Complutense de Madrid, Universitat Aut\u00f2noma de Barcelona, Tampere University, and Universidade de S\u00e3o Paulo, indicating that the book has reached an international academic readership, albeit one concentrated in the education and social-policy research communities.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">The book's commercial presence on major retail platforms and its availability through WorldCat library holdings, together with its green open-access status, extend its reach beyond specialist subscribers. Library cataloguers have classified it under Spanish economic policy, EU social and commercial policy, and Spanish social conditions \u2014 subject headings that position it as a reference point for students and researchers approaching the post-crisis Iberian political economy from multiple disciplinary angles. Its placement within the long-running <em>Travail et Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 / Work and Society</em> series, which has hosted comparably focused works on European pension reform, trade union adaptation, and labour-market policy, further situates it within a coherent scholarly conversation about the changing architecture of European social governance.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">In terms of broader relevance, the work carries an alignment with the United Nations Sustainable Development Goal on partnerships for the goals, reflecting its engagement with multilevel governance questions \u2014 specifically how supranational commitments are translated, or fail to be translated, into national policy realities. For a specialised monograph addressing a particular national case at a particular historical juncture, this combination of sustained open access, cross-national citation uptake, and series visibility suggests a stable if niche scholarly role, likely to remain useful to researchers examining EU governance, southern European political economy, and the political consequences of fiscal conditionality.</p>",
